                        <head>Irene Polinskaya</head>

                        <div>
                            <p>This is the first electronic edition of graffiti and dipinti from
                                Borysthenes/Berezan, an ancient Greek settlement on the Northern
                                coast of Black Sea (IOSPE3 vol. II.1). The introduction, epigraphic
                                editions and commentaries in English and Russian are by Irene
                                Polinskaya. The inscriptions were encoded following the EpiDoc
                                Guidelines for use of XML for ancient documentary editions, and the
                                website and supporting materials are the work of Gabriel Bodard,
                                Irene Polinskaya and colleagues at the Department of Digital
                                Humanities and King’s Digital Lab, King's College London.</p>
                            <!--<head><ref target="introduction.html">Introduction</ref></head>
                            <p>[TEXT NEEDED]</p>-->
                            <!--<divGen type="intro-toc"/>-->
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <head><ref target="/2/toc.html">Inscriptions - ALL collections</ref></head>
                            <p>The inscriptions in this volume are grouped by Category of Text, with
                                relevant sub-categories, and within the latter, by Date, in
                                chronological order. They are also accessible via <ref
                                    target="/indices/index.html">Indices</ref>, Ins. # window and
                                the <ref target="/search/en/-500/1800/?">Search Corpus</ref>
                                interface.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <head>Collections</head>
                            <div>
                                <head><ref target="part_1/index.html">Part I. Collection of the State Hermitage Museum (2020)</ref></head>
